&gt; I&#39;m stuck, most examples on internet use lambdas and not methods.

No need to spawn a number of methods like `elaboration1()`, `elaboration2()`, etc. that depend on one another, this approach is unflexible. And this approach has nothing to do with *functional interfaces* in Java (that you&#39;ve mentioned) and functional approach programming in general. In want to refactor you code to be functional in stile, there&#39;s no other way than to actually get familiar with functional programming.

*I encourage you to have a look at these official tutorials on* [*lambda expressions*](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/javaOO/lambdaexpressions.html) and 
[*streams*](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/collections/streams/index.html).

Description of the stream-logic:
* Determine the entry with the matching predicate `true`.
* Terminate the stream pipeline by yielding this entry as the object of type `Optional` (which will be empty if no result was found) by applying the operation `findFirst()`.
* Transform the contents of the *optional* and return the resulting value ([*there are a lot of ways to deal with Optional, take a look at this page for more information*](https://dev.java/learn/using-optionals/))

